                            <comment id="102171" author="jvasileff" created="Sun, 20 Apr 2014 18:18:40 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Although this looks like a bug, perhaps supporting GET is the right way to go - is making it more difficult for a user to logout with the risk of the DoS style attack? Apparently Google doesn&apos;t think so as gmail allows GET logouts.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Fixing this bug could cause problems for anyone who is unintentionally relying on it. After upgrading to a fixed version, logouts will no longer work, which would be a security concern.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="102175" author="rwinch" created="Mon, 21 Apr 2014 05:52:48 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thank you for reporting this. It is indeed a bug and is a duplicate of &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SEC-2543&quot; title=&quot;Logout Does Not Require POST even though CSRF is enabled&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SEC-2543&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SEC-2543&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In regards to your question if we should do this or not. A security framework should be secure as possible by default so if a user is unaware of an exploit the are protected. If users want to opt out, then they are able to.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="125583" author="issuemaster" created="Sat, 6 Feb 2016 06:24:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This issue has been migrated to &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-security/issues/2782&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-security/issues/2782&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
